1
00:00:07,968 --> 00:00:09,960
[MUSIC PLAYING]

2
00:01:28,176 --> 00:01:29,142
[CHILDREN PLAYING STICK-BALL]

3
00:01:29,142 --> 00:01:31,134
 Hey, batter, batter, batter, batter.

4
00:01:31,134 --> 00:01:32,400
Swing, batter, batter, batter, batter.

5
00:01:32,400 --> 00:01:35,118
 Come on, Mark, knock it far, rock it far.

6
00:01:35,118 --> 00:01:36,114
Give 'em in the heater, Mark.

7
00:01:36,114 --> 00:01:38,604
Let her fly!

8
00:01:38,604 --> 00:01:40,596
Come on, throw the stupid ball, Mark, I gotta go!

9
00:01:40,596 --> 00:01:45,078
My mom thinks I'm raking the backyard.

10
00:01:45,078 --> 00:01:46,572
[LOUD WHACK]

11
00:01:46,572 --> 00:01:47,472
 Whoops!

12
00:01:47,472 --> 00:01:48,372
 Jerk!

13
00:01:48,372 --> 00:01:49,353
That's my rake handle.

14
00:01:49,353 --> 00:01:52,000
My mom's gonna kill me! - Sorry!

15
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:52,946
 Sorry, nothing.

16
00:01:52,946 --> 00:01:54,365
What am I gonna tell my mom?

17
00:01:54,365 --> 00:01:56,350
 Tell her to start buying thicker rakes.

18
00:01:56,350 --> 00:01:59,245
[LAUGHING] - That's not funny!

19
00:01:59,245 --> 00:02:00,742
Really not funny.

20
00:02:00,742 --> 00:02:02,738
[MUSIC PLAYING]

21
00:02:22,199 --> 00:02:23,197
 Hey.

22
00:02:23,197 --> 00:02:24,195
[KISSING)

23
00:02:24,195 --> 00:02:25,193
 Hi.

24
00:02:25,193 --> 00:02:27,290
[CHUCKLING] Hi!

25
00:02:27,290 --> 00:02:28,190
 So--

26
00:02:28,190 --> 00:02:29,460
 Mm?

27
00:02:29,460 --> 00:02:31,510
 You feel maternal?

28
00:02:31,510 --> 00:02:32,580
 What?

29
00:02:32,580 --> 00:02:34,280
 You feel maternal?

30
00:02:34,280 --> 00:02:36,852
 [LAUGHING] I don't know.

31
00:02:36,852 --> 00:02:39,344
Yeah, maybe, maybe.

32
00:02:39,344 --> 00:02:41,630
 Good.

33
00:02:41,630 --> 00:02:43,090
 Got to be positive.

34
00:02:43,090 --> 00:02:45,431
Attitude, remember that, attitude.

35
00:02:45,431 --> 00:02:46,630
 Getting pregnant iis a little more

36
00:02:46,630 --> 00:02:48,272
complicated than that, Bill

37
00:02:48,272 --> 00:02:50,584
 Mm-- attitude.

38
00:03:20,962 --> 00:03:22,456
 Hey, guys, what's up?

39
00:03:22,456 --> 00:03:23,950
Wanna play?

40
00:03:23,950 --> 00:03:26,938
[OVERLAPPING SOUNDS OF CHILDREN  PLAYING]

41
00:03:26,938 --> 00:03:28,930
[WISTFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

42
00:03:56,818 --> 00:03:58,810
[BUS TOOTS HORN]

43
00:04:18,760 --> 00:04:21,880
 So the Norris's say they'll donate $50,000

44
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:23,260
to the school's general fund.

45
00:04:23,260 --> 00:04:24,760
 Oh, that's great.

46
00:04:24,760 --> 00:04:29,040
 If the school will name a building after them.

47
00:04:29,040 --> 00:04:31,460
 Do they have any particular building in mind?

48
00:04:31,460 --> 00:04:32,620
 No, they're flexible.

49
00:04:32,620 --> 00:04:36,180
 We'll have to see how flexible.

50
00:04:36,180 --> 00:04:37,580
What else you got?

51
00:04:37,580 --> 00:04:39,342
 Class of '55 reunion.

52
00:04:39,342 --> 00:04:44,346
 Sorry to interrupt, Hilton Burberry's here to see you.

53
00:04:44,346 --> 00:04:45,640
 I'll call the Norrises.

54
00:04:45,640 --> 00:04:47,420
 Would you?

55
00:04:47,420 --> 00:04:49,890
Tell them we appreciate their generosity

56
00:04:49,890 --> 00:04:52,580
but fortunately, we don't have any unnamed buildings

57
00:04:52,580 --> 00:04:53,590
available.

58
00:04:53,590 --> 00:04:54,490
Hi!

59
00:04:54,490 --> 00:04:55,580
 Hi!

60
00:04:55,580 --> 00:04:58,370
I don't know if you remember me but I run the baseball program

61
00:04:58,370 --> 00:04:59,390
your son used to play in.

62
00:04:59,390 --> 00:05:00,290
 Of course I remember.

63
00:05:00,290 --> 00:05:02,550
C'mon in.

64
00:05:02,550 --> 00:05:05,533
Yeah, it's a great program, he really loved it.

65
00:05:05,533 --> 00:05:07,910
 Look, now, we don't really know each other

66
00:05:07,910 --> 00:05:10,850
and I know it's been awhile since your son passed on.

67
00:05:10,850 --> 00:05:14,750
And I've always felt bad about not offering my condolences.

68
00:05:14,750 --> 00:05:17,220
He was truly one of a kind.

69
00:05:17,220 --> 00:05:18,640
I mean that.

70
00:05:18,640 --> 00:05:19,540
 Thank you.

71
00:05:19,540 --> 00:05:21,430
That's very nice of you to say.

72
00:05:21,430 --> 00:05:24,064
 You and your wife doing OK?

73
00:05:24,064 --> 00:05:26,860
 Oh, yeah, fine, just fine.

74
00:05:26,860 --> 00:05:28,520
Great as a matter of fact.

75
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,980
 Can we talk for a minute?

76
00:05:30,980 --> 00:05:31,880
 Sure.

77
00:05:31,880 --> 00:05:34,235
I've got to run over to administration, why

78
00:05:34,235 --> 00:05:35,600
don't you walk me over?

79
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:36,500
 All right.

80
00:05:42,660 --> 00:05:45,040
 You a big baseball fan, Bill?

81
00:05:45,040 --> 00:05:47,820
 Oh, I wouldn't say a big one.

82
00:05:47,820 --> 00:05:51,760
I read the occasional box score, take in a game now and then.

83
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:53,930
 Baseball will be starting up again pretty soon.

84
00:05:53,930 --> 00:05:54,830
 You're kidding.

85
00:05:54,830 --> 00:05:56,743
It seems like it just ended.

86
00:05:56,743 --> 00:05:58,630
 I know what you mean.

87
00:05:58,630 --> 00:06:00,130
I feel like I get about one week's

88
00:06:00,130 --> 00:06:02,110
vacation between handing out trophies

89
00:06:02,110 --> 00:06:04,630
and finding new coaches.

90
00:06:04,630 --> 00:06:07,040
 Wait a minute.

91
00:06:07,040 --> 00:06:09,980
Is that why you stopped by to see me?

92
00:06:09,980 --> 00:06:11,920
You want me to coach?

93
00:06:11,920 --> 00:06:15,470
 Well, I had hoped to ease into a little more gracefully,

94
00:06:15,470 --> 00:06:18,388
but yes, the thought had crossed my mind.

95
00:06:22,140 --> 00:06:24,450
 You'd be surprised how much fun it can be.

96
00:06:24,450 --> 00:06:26,790
 Oh, I'm sure it is.

97
00:06:26,790 --> 00:06:29,494
But, um-- I'm kind of busy at work,

98
00:06:29,494 --> 00:06:30,660
I wouldn't have the time to put it.

99
00:06:30,660 --> 00:06:35,820
 Now listen, listen, I'll shoot straight with you.

100
00:06:35,820 --> 00:06:38,460
You've had a tough year and I imagine it's

101
00:06:38,460 --> 00:06:40,640
not going to get much easier.

102
00:06:40,640 --> 00:06:45,870
Keeping busy, being around kids, it might help.

103
00:06:45,870 --> 00:06:48,000
They're good kids, Bill.

104
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,430
You probably know most of them, your son

105
00:06:50,430 --> 00:06:51,540
was a pretty popular boy.

106
00:06:54,480 --> 00:06:56,110
 Yes, he was.

107
00:06:56,110 --> 00:06:57,010
 Think about it.

108
00:07:12,440 --> 00:07:13,364
BILL: How's the book?

109
00:07:13,364 --> 00:07:15,220
 It's OK.

110
00:07:15,220 --> 00:07:17,119
You finish the puzzle? BILL: Almost.

111
00:07:20,090 --> 00:07:23,050
 I think I'm going to go to bed.

112
00:07:23,050 --> 00:07:24,560
 So soon?

113
00:07:24,560 --> 00:07:25,882
It's early.

114
00:07:25,882 --> 00:07:28,274
 I'm tired.

115
00:07:28,274 --> 00:07:30,770
 Don't stay up to late, OK?

116
00:07:30,770 --> 00:07:33,590
 OK.

117
00:07:33,590 --> 00:07:36,846
 Hey, um, guess who stopped by to see me today?

118
00:07:36,846 --> 00:07:37,818
 Who?

119
00:07:37,818 --> 00:07:40,500
 Hilton Burberry.

120
00:07:40,500 --> 00:07:42,480
 What did he want?

121
00:07:42,480 --> 00:07:44,760
 Just to say he was sorry about Nathaniel.

122
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:46,047
 Oh.

123
00:07:46,047 --> 00:07:48,910
That's sweet.

124
00:07:48,910 --> 00:07:52,620
 He, um-- also asked if I'd be interested in coaching

125
00:07:52,620 --> 00:07:56,230
a baseball team this year?

126
00:07:56,230 --> 00:07:59,060
 Why you?

127
00:07:59,060 --> 00:08:00,950
 I don't know.

128
00:08:00,950 --> 00:08:05,180
He said, he thought I might want to.

129
00:08:05,180 --> 00:08:06,394
 Do you?

130
00:08:06,394 --> 00:08:08,520
 I'm thinking about it.

131
00:08:08,520 --> 00:08:09,420
 Why?

132
00:08:09,420 --> 00:08:10,340
 Might be fun.

133
00:08:13,701 --> 00:08:14,600
 He's gone, Bill.

134
00:08:17,320 --> 00:08:19,421
 This is not about Nathaniel.

135
00:08:26,500 --> 00:08:29,050
 OK, whatever you say.

136
00:08:29,050 --> 00:08:33,010
If you really want to do it, I think you should do it.

137
00:08:33,010 --> 00:08:33,969
 Well, I do.

138
00:08:33,969 --> 00:08:36,264
And don't worry, it will be fine.

139
00:08:36,264 --> 00:08:37,409
It'll be a lot of fun.

140
00:08:42,389 --> 00:08:46,380
Do we have any ice cream?

141
00:08:46,380 --> 00:08:49,950
 OK, now, here are your rosters.

142
00:08:49,950 --> 00:08:52,470
You have 15 kids on a team.

143
00:08:52,470 --> 00:08:53,850
And you'll each have an assistant

144
00:08:53,850 --> 00:08:56,580
to help you corral them all.

145
00:08:56,580 --> 00:08:58,110
Bill, you're the new guy here so we don't

146
00:08:58,110 --> 00:08:59,670
have an assistant for you yet.

147
00:08:59,670 --> 00:09:03,210
I'll keep looking, but if you find somebody who is willing,

148
00:09:03,210 --> 00:09:04,980
grab him.

149
00:09:04,980 --> 00:09:08,920
Now Fred White is going to be umpiring for us again this year

150
00:09:08,920 --> 00:09:12,410
and I don't want you to give him a hard time.

151
00:09:12,410 --> 00:09:14,130
The job is hard enough without you guys

152
00:09:14,130 --> 00:09:16,332
screaming down his throat all the time.

153
00:09:16,332 --> 00:09:21,370
And besides, if we lose him, then I'm stuck doing it.

154
00:09:21,370 --> 00:09:23,753
And believe me, none of us wants that to happen.

155
00:09:23,753 --> 00:09:25,970
[CHUCKLING]

156
00:09:25,970 --> 00:09:27,876
 I see Hilton talked you into this, too, huh?

157
00:09:27,876 --> 00:09:29,376
HILTON: Our season starts in two short days--

158
00:09:29,376 --> 00:09:32,185
 Yeah, Hilton has a way of doing that, doesn't he?

159
00:09:32,185 --> 00:09:33,895
 Yes, he does.

160
00:09:33,895 --> 00:09:35,180
He is relentless. I--

161
00:09:35,180 --> 00:09:35,330
HILTON: -- a lot of work you--

162
00:09:35,330 --> 00:09:36,696
 --tell you he just keeps coming at you.

163
00:09:36,696 --> 00:09:38,470
HILTON: --refurbishing this year.

164
00:09:38,470 --> 00:09:41,320
We've received bats, a new dugout.

165
00:09:41,320 --> 00:09:44,645
In fact, we have a lot--

166
00:09:44,645 --> 00:09:47,120
 How are you and Harper doing?

167
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:48,290
 Fine, just fine.

168
00:09:48,290 --> 00:09:49,616
Great.

169
00:09:49,616 --> 00:09:51,650
 Good. That's good to hear.

170
00:09:51,650 --> 00:09:54,620
HILTON: Hell, I know it takes a lot of--

171
00:09:54,620 --> 00:09:57,290
 Is there anything Laura and I can do?

172
00:09:57,290 --> 00:09:59,940
 No, we're OK.

173
00:09:59,940 --> 00:10:01,020
 Good.

174
00:10:01,020 --> 00:10:01,920
That's good.

175
00:10:11,040 --> 00:10:11,980
 Hey!

176
00:10:11,980 --> 00:10:13,550
Hey you!

177
00:10:13,550 --> 00:10:16,155
Hey!

178
00:10:16,155 --> 00:10:17,260
 Me?

179
00:10:17,260 --> 00:10:18,712
 Yeah, you.

180
00:10:18,712 --> 00:10:19,612
Come here!

181
00:10:23,950 --> 00:10:24,914
 OK.

182
00:10:27,820 --> 00:10:30,040
What can I do for you, sir?

183
00:10:30,040 --> 00:10:32,090
 Last night they told me I couldn't eat pizza.

184
00:10:34,720 --> 00:10:36,440
 Who told you that?

185
00:10:36,440 --> 00:10:38,430
 That quack, teenage doctor of mine.

186
00:10:38,430 --> 00:10:41,730
He wrote on my chart that I couldn't have spicy food.

187
00:10:41,730 --> 00:10:44,140
Oh, they brought me a tuna casserole.

188
00:10:44,140 --> 00:10:46,900
Tuna casserole!

189
00:10:46,900 --> 00:10:49,080
 Well, tuna's good.

190
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:53,190
 Sure, lightly grilled with a nice Dijon mustard sauce,

191
00:10:53,190 --> 00:10:55,320
but not in a casserole with potato chips

192
00:10:55,320 --> 00:10:57,540
sprinkled all over the top of it.

193
00:10:57,540 --> 00:10:58,730
Trust me, it's terrible.

194
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:03,060
 What did you do?

195
00:11:03,060 --> 00:11:05,380
 I told them that no teenage, quack doctor

196
00:11:05,380 --> 00:11:06,750
was going to tell me whether I could

197
00:11:06,750 --> 00:11:09,326
or could not eat spicy food.

198
00:11:09,326 --> 00:11:11,700
So I went into the kitchen and got myself a bottle

199
00:11:11,700 --> 00:11:13,440
of Tabasco sauce and I sprinkled it

200
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:15,757
all over that blasted casserole.

201
00:11:15,757 --> 00:11:18,890
 Well, you certainly made your point, then.

202
00:11:18,890 --> 00:11:21,100
 Yes, I did.

203
00:11:21,100 --> 00:11:22,990
Unfortunately, it gave me the runs.

204
00:11:25,740 --> 00:11:29,040
I thought for sure I was going to die in my sleep.

205
00:11:29,040 --> 00:11:32,120
Point is, I'm still a man.

206
00:11:32,120 --> 00:11:34,230
If I want to eat spicy food and get the runs,

207
00:11:34,230 --> 00:11:36,510
that's my business.

208
00:11:36,510 --> 00:11:37,420
 I agree.

209
00:11:37,420 --> 00:11:39,180
 Darn straight!

210
00:11:39,180 --> 00:11:42,360
I'm alive and I'm all here.

211
00:11:42,360 --> 00:11:45,300
At least on most days.

212
00:11:45,300 --> 00:11:48,900
You-- you run by here every day, don't you?

213
00:11:48,900 --> 00:11:50,302
 Yes, sir, I do.

214
00:11:50,302 --> 00:11:53,370
 Well, if you ever get bored and you want to talk,

215
00:11:53,370 --> 00:11:57,180
why just wander up here.

216
00:11:57,180 --> 00:11:58,890
Ask for Mr. Godfrey.

217
00:11:58,890 --> 00:12:00,040
 Mr. Godfrey.

218
00:12:00,040 --> 00:12:00,940
I'll do that.

219
00:12:04,740 --> 00:12:10,680
 And, uh-- bring me a pizza or something, will you?

220
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:11,610
 I'll see what I can do.

221
00:12:21,669 --> 00:12:22,900
 Harper?

222
00:12:22,900 --> 00:12:23,800
 Up here.

223
00:12:41,512 --> 00:12:43,496
 Hi.

224
00:12:43,496 --> 00:12:44,984
 Hi.

225
00:12:44,984 --> 00:12:47,860
 What are you doing?

226
00:12:47,860 --> 00:12:49,700
 Field Library's having a book drive.

227
00:12:49,700 --> 00:12:52,505
I was going to donate some of Nathaniel's books.

228
00:12:52,505 --> 00:12:54,216
Is that OK?

229
00:12:54,216 --> 00:12:55,635
 Yeah, sure.

230
00:12:58,950 --> 00:13:01,110
 He didn't have that many, but for some reason

231
00:13:01,110 --> 00:13:04,610
this seems to have taken most of the day.

232
00:13:04,610 --> 00:13:06,380
 It's OK.

233
00:13:06,380 --> 00:13:10,060
 We should have bought him more books, Bill.

234
00:13:10,060 --> 00:13:11,790
I just-- I keep thinking a little boy

235
00:13:11,790 --> 00:13:12,915
should have a lot of books.

236
00:13:15,980 --> 00:13:18,070
If I ever get pregnant again we'll fill the house--

237
00:13:18,070 --> 00:13:23,580
[SAD, LILTING MUSIC PLAYING]

238
00:13:23,580 --> 00:13:24,480
 I promise.

239
00:13:27,220 --> 00:13:29,850
We'll have books everywhere.

240
00:13:29,850 --> 00:13:33,036
 Why'd we wait so long?

241
00:13:33,036 --> 00:13:34,690
Why didn't we have another baby when

242
00:13:34,690 --> 00:13:37,088
Nathaniel was a little boy?

243
00:13:37,088 --> 00:13:40,004
 I don't know.

244
00:13:40,004 --> 00:13:41,940
I guess we just always felt complete.

245
00:13:46,504 --> 00:13:52,530
 You know, I'd forgotten how much he loved Custer He must

246
00:13:52,530 --> 00:13:56,370
have had five books on Custer.

247
00:13:56,370 --> 00:14:00,120
"Custer and the Battle of the Little Bighorn."

248
00:14:00,120 --> 00:14:02,760
"George Armstrong Custer, Man Of Courage."

249
00:14:06,530 --> 00:14:07,730
He loved Custer.

250
00:14:10,260 --> 00:14:11,870
I have no idea why.

251
00:14:18,227 --> 00:14:20,672
I should have asked him why.

252
00:14:32,408 --> 00:14:34,632
I'll bring these books to the library tomorrow.

253
00:14:37,430 --> 00:14:39,580
Hopefully, they can give them to another little boy.

254
00:15:03,484 --> 00:15:04,978
 [SIGHS]

255
00:15:05,974 --> 00:15:40,834
[DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE]

256
00:15:40,834 --> 00:15:43,324
[SAD, LILTING MUSIC PLAYING]

257
00:16:07,228 --> 00:16:09,220
[ELECTRIC TRAINS HUMMING]

258
00:16:37,108 --> 00:16:39,100
[TOY TRAIN WHISTLE]

259
00:16:46,190 --> 00:16:48,610
 You haven't been out here in a long time.

260
00:16:48,610 --> 00:16:50,670
 No, I guess I haven't.

261
00:16:50,670 --> 00:16:54,690
 You and Nathaniel used to come out here all the time.

262
00:16:54,690 --> 00:16:58,410
So secretive, the door always closed.

263
00:16:58,410 --> 00:16:59,310
What did you talk about?

264
00:17:02,060 --> 00:17:04,230
 I don't know.

265
00:17:04,230 --> 00:17:06,720
Guy stuff.

266
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:08,636
Secret guy stuff.

267
00:17:08,636 --> 00:17:11,534
 Oh, I see.

268
00:17:11,534 --> 00:17:16,150
 Honey, uh-- there's this kid on my team.

269
00:17:16,150 --> 00:17:17,436
His name is Diamond.

270
00:17:17,436 --> 00:17:19,666
You ever heard of him?

271
00:17:19,666 --> 00:17:22,300
 No, no, doesn't go to our school.

272
00:17:22,300 --> 00:17:24,860
I could ask some of the other teachers, if you like.

273
00:17:24,860 --> 00:17:26,780
 Yeah.

274
00:17:26,780 --> 00:17:30,670
 You taking this baseball team pretty seriously, aren't you?

275
00:17:30,670 --> 00:17:32,790
 No, just doing my homework.

276
00:17:32,790 --> 00:17:34,030
 OK, OK.

277
00:17:34,030 --> 00:17:38,117
I just don't want it to make you unhappy.

278
00:17:38,117 --> 00:17:40,612
 It won't.

279
00:17:40,612 --> 00:17:43,606
 OK.

280
00:17:43,606 --> 00:17:46,101
[TOY TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

281
00:17:50,600 --> 00:17:51,980
 You know, every once in a while

282
00:17:51,980 --> 00:17:55,848
it would be nice to be a part of that secret guy stuff.

283
00:18:03,720 --> 00:18:21,432
[TOY TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

284
00:18:21,432 --> 00:18:24,260
 Hi!

285
00:18:24,260 --> 00:18:25,160
You from around here?

286
00:18:38,990 --> 00:18:39,890
Oh.

287
00:18:42,480 --> 00:18:43,380
Where do you live?

288
00:18:56,750 --> 00:18:58,110
Off the logging road.

289
00:18:58,110 --> 00:18:59,010
Really?

290
00:19:01,290 --> 00:19:02,190
What's your name?

291
00:19:09,637 --> 00:19:10,537
Lucky.

292
00:19:13,590 --> 00:19:14,490
Lucky what?

293
00:19:24,900 --> 00:19:25,820
Lucky Diamond.

294
00:19:33,270 --> 00:19:36,453
He said he lived off the old logging road.

295
00:19:36,453 --> 00:19:37,353
 So?

296
00:19:37,353 --> 00:19:39,915
 So nobody lives up there.

297
00:19:39,915 --> 00:19:42,270
Nathaniel and I used to hike up there all the time,

298
00:19:42,270 --> 00:19:43,290
there aren't any houses.

299
00:19:43,290 --> 00:19:46,440
 Look, isn't it possible that in all your extensive hiking,

300
00:19:46,440 --> 00:19:47,580
you missed one house?

301
00:19:47,580 --> 00:19:49,800
 Harper, there's not even a power line leading up there.

302
00:19:49,800 --> 00:19:52,480
 Why would he lie about that?

303
00:19:52,480 --> 00:19:53,910
 I don't know.

304
00:19:53,910 --> 00:19:56,910
But there is something weird about this kid.

305
00:19:56,910 --> 00:19:58,340
 I don't believe you.

306
00:19:58,340 --> 00:20:00,720
You meet a mute boy who won't give you an exact address

307
00:20:00,720 --> 00:20:03,970
and you're ready to call in the grand jury.

308
00:20:03,970 --> 00:20:07,590
 OK, forget it.

309
00:20:07,590 --> 00:20:08,725
I just hope he can play baseball.

310
00:20:11,948 --> 00:20:14,413
[MUSIC PLAYING]

311
00:20:20,329 --> 00:20:22,335
 Aw, it's gonna be a good year.

312
00:20:37,120 --> 00:20:41,530
Oh, yeah, it's going to be a very good year.

313
00:20:41,530 --> 00:20:43,180
You all right, Josh?

314
00:20:43,180 --> 00:20:44,080
 Yeah.

315
00:20:44,080 --> 00:20:45,250
 All right, let's pair up.

316
00:20:45,250 --> 00:20:48,100
Throw the ball around and see what kind of arms we got.

317
00:20:48,100 --> 00:20:49,330
Dickie you want to throw with Lucky?

318
00:20:49,330 --> 00:20:53,530
 I always throw with David.

319
00:20:53,530 --> 00:20:54,790
 OK.

320
00:20:54,790 --> 00:20:55,690
Josh, how about you?

321
00:20:55,690 --> 00:20:57,500
 I promised I'd help Melissa.

322
00:21:16,910 --> 00:21:17,810
 Lucky?

323
00:21:39,030 --> 00:21:42,030
[CHUCKLING]

324
00:21:44,030 --> 00:21:46,030
 Aw, burn out!

325
00:21:50,030 --> 00:21:51,030
 Ow!

326
00:21:51,030 --> 00:21:52,000
All right, I quit.

327
00:21:52,000 --> 00:21:52,968
I quit!

328
00:21:58,292 --> 00:22:00,440
 All right, Dickie, get one.

329
00:22:02,410 --> 00:22:03,310
Melissa!

330
00:22:07,050 --> 00:22:08,190
OK.

331
00:22:08,190 --> 00:22:09,090
Josh!

332
00:22:12,540 --> 00:22:14,760
Jill!

333
00:22:14,760 --> 00:22:16,190
Atta girl!

334
00:22:16,190 --> 00:22:18,490
Melissa!

335
00:22:18,490 --> 00:22:23,650
OK, Melissa, um, look, get in the ready position.

336
00:22:23,650 --> 00:22:28,320
Get your hands on your knees, crouch down, just like this.

337
00:22:28,320 --> 00:22:29,470
Go ahead.

338
00:22:29,470 --> 00:22:30,700
That's it.

339
00:22:30,700 --> 00:22:35,000
All right, we got a man on first, ground ball at third,

340
00:22:35,000 --> 00:22:37,360
let's get two.

341
00:22:37,360 --> 00:22:39,020
Melissa, you ready?

342
00:22:39,020 --> 00:22:40,150
 Ready.

343
00:22:40,150 --> 00:22:41,050
 OK.

344
00:22:44,550 --> 00:22:46,050
 Hello, Melissa.

345
00:22:51,550 --> 00:22:53,770
 What?

346
00:22:53,770 --> 00:22:56,050
 Well, I said get to.

347
00:22:56,050 --> 00:22:59,290
 Get to what?

348
00:22:59,290 --> 00:23:01,710
 We'll come back to this tomorrow.

349
00:23:01,710 --> 00:23:02,610
Come on in.

350
00:23:02,610 --> 00:23:04,820
Huddle up.

351
00:23:04,820 --> 00:23:08,175
Hustle, let's go!

352
00:23:08,175 --> 00:23:11,640
Are there any questions before we knock off practice today?

353
00:23:11,640 --> 00:23:13,470
Yes, Charlie?

354
00:23:13,470 --> 00:23:15,250
 Did you bring any snacks?

355
00:23:15,250 --> 00:23:17,130
 Oh, snacks.

356
00:23:17,130 --> 00:23:18,037
No, I didn't.

357
00:23:18,037 --> 00:23:19,320
[CHILDREN MOANING AND WHINING]

358
00:23:19,320 --> 00:23:22,600
 The coach always bring snacks.

359
00:23:22,600 --> 00:23:23,820
 He does?

360
00:23:23,820 --> 00:23:26,570
 Sometimes cool snacks, like ice cream.

361
00:23:26,570 --> 00:23:30,360
 Yeah, don't you know anything about baseball?

362
00:23:30,360 --> 00:23:31,515
 You babies.

363
00:23:31,515 --> 00:23:35,530
We're not here to eat snacks, we're here to play ball.

364
00:23:35,530 --> 00:23:37,370
Win some games.

365
00:23:37,370 --> 00:23:38,520
Right?

366
00:23:38,520 --> 00:23:40,440
 No, I'm just here for the snacks.

367
00:23:40,440 --> 00:23:41,940
[CHILDREN ALL LAUGH]

368
00:23:41,940 --> 00:23:44,700
 All right, I'll see what I can do about snacks for next time,

369
00:23:44,700 --> 00:23:45,690
OK?

370
00:23:45,690 --> 00:23:47,549
See you Wednesday. Get out of here.

371
00:23:54,060 --> 00:23:57,490
 When does the baseball season start?

372
00:23:57,490 --> 00:24:00,280
 Tomorrow afternoon.

373
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:02,310
 Hilton Burberry still heading that up?

374
00:24:02,310 --> 00:24:03,640
 Yes, sir, he is.

375
00:24:03,640 --> 00:24:05,550
 He used to be a general manager of the Red Sox,

376
00:24:05,550 --> 00:24:06,750
you know. - Is that right?

377
00:24:06,750 --> 00:24:07,950
 Yeah.

378
00:24:07,950 --> 00:24:10,730
Well, it was a long time ago.

379
00:24:10,730 --> 00:24:12,820
He doesn't talk much about it.

380
00:24:12,820 --> 00:24:14,702
It ended very badly.

381
00:24:14,702 --> 00:24:17,710
A ballplayer got drunk at a party at his house one night

382
00:24:17,710 --> 00:24:20,380
and wrapped his car around a tree.

383
00:24:20,380 --> 00:24:23,610
Ended very badly, indeed.

384
00:24:23,610 --> 00:24:26,590
Those kids of yours ready to play ball?

385
00:24:26,590 --> 00:24:28,630
 Not at all.

386
00:24:28,630 --> 00:24:31,950
 Well, you got your hands full.

387
00:24:31,950 --> 00:24:34,855
But enjoy every minute of it, Bill, every minute of it.

388
00:24:34,855 --> 00:24:36,640
Because you may wind up where I did,

389
00:24:36,640 --> 00:24:40,090
sitting on a porch watching other people living life.

390
00:24:40,090 --> 00:24:42,550
And dreaming about the good old days

391
00:24:42,550 --> 00:24:45,100
when you could eat all the pepperoni you wanted to.

392
00:24:53,794 --> 00:24:57,420
 How'd you like to be my assistant coach?

393
00:24:57,420 --> 00:24:58,420
 What?

394
00:24:58,420 --> 00:25:00,640
 Practice every day, games twice a week.

395
00:25:00,640 --> 00:25:03,447
What do you say?

396
00:25:03,447 --> 00:25:05,380
 I don't know whether you've been paying attention, Bill,

397
00:25:05,380 --> 00:25:07,640
but I am old.

398
00:25:07,640 --> 00:25:11,020
 That shouldn't stop you from coaching baseball.

399
00:25:11,020 --> 00:25:14,390
Come on, I could use the help.

400
00:25:14,390 --> 00:25:15,830
 You sure about this?

401
00:25:15,830 --> 00:25:19,030
 First game's tomorrow afternoon.

402
00:25:19,030 --> 00:25:20,618
 Coaching baseball, huh?

403
00:25:20,618 --> 00:25:21,574
 Yep.

404
00:25:26,354 --> 00:25:30,170
 You're all right, Bill Parish.

405
00:25:30,170 --> 00:25:32,030
Yes, sir, you're all right.

406
00:25:32,030 --> 00:25:37,280
[ACADEMIC MUSIC PLAYING]

407
00:25:37,280 --> 00:25:40,580
 Ladies and gentlemen, Spring is here.

408
00:25:40,580 --> 00:25:43,437
And once again it's time for baseball.

409
00:25:43,437 --> 00:25:44,898
[FANS CHEERING]

410
00:25:46,846 --> 00:25:48,800
As the commissioner of this league,

411
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:53,180
I want this to be our best season ever.

412
00:25:53,180 --> 00:25:57,940
I don't want there to be any arguments, no harsh language,

413
00:25:57,940 --> 00:26:02,710
and fighting will absolutely not be tolerated.

414
00:26:02,710 --> 00:26:05,185
Now I also have a few words I'd like to say to the players.

415
00:26:08,090 --> 00:26:09,710
Play hard.

416
00:26:09,710 --> 00:26:10,934
Play well.

417
00:26:10,934 --> 00:26:13,590
And play fair.

418
00:26:13,590 --> 00:26:15,740
Enough speeches.

419
00:26:15,740 --> 00:26:19,545
Let's play ball.

420
00:26:19,545 --> 00:26:21,373
 OK, come on.

421
00:26:21,373 --> 00:26:22,920
Let's huddle up!

422
00:26:22,920 --> 00:26:27,320
 You heard the man, gather in here.

423
00:26:27,320 --> 00:26:31,090
Panthers, I want you all to meet our new assistant coach.

424
00:26:31,090 --> 00:26:33,010
His name is Mr. Godfrey.

425
00:26:33,010 --> 00:26:35,160
He's going to be with us from now on.

426
00:26:35,160 --> 00:26:36,634
 You look old.

427
00:26:36,634 --> 00:26:37,540
 So?

428
00:26:37,540 --> 00:26:38,440
You look stupid.

429
00:26:42,770 --> 00:26:43,670
 Charlie?

430
00:26:43,670 --> 00:26:45,480
You all right there?

431
00:26:45,480 --> 00:26:48,510
 Sure, coach.

432
00:26:48,510 --> 00:26:49,780
 OK, now.

433
00:26:49,780 --> 00:26:53,020
Let's all remember what we talked about in practice.

434
00:26:53,020 --> 00:26:55,060
What is the most important thing to remember?

435
00:26:55,060 --> 00:26:59,260
 When someone throws you the ball, don't duck.

436
00:26:59,260 --> 00:27:01,840
 That's very good but that was more of a personal message

437
00:27:01,840 --> 00:27:04,630
to you, Melissa.

438
00:27:04,630 --> 00:27:07,510
Everybody stay alert, always be thinking

439
00:27:07,510 --> 00:27:09,910
what you would do with the ball if it was hit to you.

440
00:27:09,910 --> 00:27:11,200
And outfielders, remember--

441
00:27:11,200 --> 00:27:13,030
 Don't do cartwheels between pitches.

442
00:27:15,870 --> 00:27:18,090
 Well, I think that about covers it.

443
00:27:18,090 --> 00:27:20,010
Hands in a circle.

444
00:27:20,010 --> 00:27:20,910
What are we?

445
00:27:20,910 --> 00:27:22,620
ALL: A team!

446
00:27:22,620 --> 00:27:23,730
 What's it going to take to win?

447
00:27:26,580 --> 00:27:29,280
 A lot of runs.

448
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:31,040
 Yeah, and teamwork.

449
00:27:31,040 --> 00:27:32,510
ALL: Teamwork!

450
00:27:32,510 --> 00:27:34,858
 All right, let's get out there and play some--

451
00:27:34,858 --> 00:27:36,850
[CHEERING]

452
00:27:36,850 --> 00:27:39,318
 --baseball!

453
00:27:39,318 --> 00:27:43,390
Yeah, I think that went pretty well, don't you?

454
00:27:43,390 --> 00:27:44,830
 Uh, Bill--

455
00:27:44,830 --> 00:27:46,330
 You know, I got to admit I was a little bit

456
00:27:46,330 --> 00:27:47,826
nervous about our first game, but I

457
00:27:47,826 --> 00:27:48,790
think we're going to do OK.

458
00:27:48,790 --> 00:27:49,720
 Uh, Bill--

459
00:27:49,720 --> 00:27:51,340
 Yeah.

460
00:27:51,340 --> 00:27:53,650
 You sent the team out on the field.

461
00:27:53,650 --> 00:27:54,780
You see, we're batting first.

462
00:28:00,290 --> 00:28:02,260
 Ah!

463
00:28:02,260 --> 00:28:05,640
Come on back in guys, we're up first.

464
00:28:05,640 --> 00:28:07,080
Thanks.

465
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:08,490
 No problem.

466
00:28:08,490 --> 00:28:09,390
 Come on, hustle up.

467
00:28:09,390 --> 00:28:10,290
Let's go!

468
00:28:15,330 --> 00:28:18,940
Anybody got an extra belt?

469
00:28:18,940 --> 00:28:22,748
UMPIRE: Strike three, he's out.

470
00:28:22,748 --> 00:28:26,306
ANNOUNCER: Next batter for the Panthers, number nine,

471
00:28:26,306 --> 00:28:27,206
Melissa Jones.

472
00:28:27,206 --> 00:28:28,930
 Come on, now, Melissa, don't be afraid of it.

473
00:28:28,930 --> 00:28:29,886
Be a hitter.

474
00:28:29,886 --> 00:28:30,842
 What?

475
00:28:30,842 --> 00:28:32,510
UMPIRE: Strike!

476
00:28:32,510 --> 00:28:33,410
 I wasn't ready!

477
00:28:33,410 --> 00:28:34,655
UMPIRE: Strike one!

478
00:28:34,655 --> 00:28:36,640
 He was talking to me, weren't you?

479
00:28:36,640 --> 00:28:38,330
 I was just yelling.

480
00:28:38,330 --> 00:28:40,290
 Well, why were you yelling at me?

481
00:28:40,290 --> 00:28:42,085
I didn't get the strike until after you yelled.

482
00:28:42,085 --> 00:28:44,270
UMPIRE: Can we get on with this game now, please?

483
00:28:44,270 --> 00:28:45,830
 I just said be a hitter.

484
00:28:49,092 --> 00:28:51,160
 Come on, Melissa, good eye, good eye.

485
00:28:51,160 --> 00:28:52,083
 What?

486
00:28:52,083 --> 00:28:53,670
UMPIRE: Strike two!

487
00:28:53,670 --> 00:28:56,880
 He keeps on talking to me!

488
00:28:56,880 --> 00:29:00,970
 Melissa, it's just baseball chatter.

489
00:29:00,970 --> 00:29:04,990
- Well, it's very distracting. - Well, I'll stop.

490
00:29:04,990 --> 00:29:08,630
 Thank you.

491
00:29:08,630 --> 00:29:09,910
 Oh yeah, it's going great.

492
00:29:14,890 --> 00:29:16,882
UMPIRE: He's out!

493
00:29:16,882 --> 00:29:18,810
 Nice play.

494
00:29:18,810 --> 00:29:20,660
Get fired up here, now.

495
00:29:20,660 --> 00:29:21,795
Charlie, you're up.

496
00:29:21,795 --> 00:29:24,315
Josh, on deck, Lucky, in the hole.

497
00:29:24,315 --> 00:29:27,510
So last at bats, we need runs.

498
00:29:27,510 --> 00:29:29,484
Get on base, Charlie.

499
00:29:29,484 --> 00:29:34,410
 I can't get a hit, send somebody else in.

500
00:29:34,410 --> 00:29:38,130
 Charlie, you got to stop worrying so much.

501
00:29:38,130 --> 00:29:41,250
Just go out there and do the best you can.

502
00:29:41,250 --> 00:29:44,415
That's all we're asking.

503
00:29:44,415 --> 00:29:46,219
PANTHER: Go, Charlie!

504
00:29:46,219 --> 00:29:48,410
ANNOUNCER: Now batting for the Panthers, number two,

505
00:29:48,410 --> 00:29:49,384
Charlie Gray.

506
00:29:53,280 --> 00:29:55,350
 We need base runners, Charlie.

507
00:29:55,350 --> 00:29:58,305
We need base runners, let's go.

508
00:29:58,305 --> 00:30:05,095
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

509
00:30:05,095 --> 00:30:06,550
[BELL DINGS]

510
00:30:07,520 --> 00:30:08,490
UMPIRE: Time!

511
00:30:13,360 --> 00:30:16,314
 Charlie, you OK?

512
00:30:16,314 --> 00:30:20,050
 Sure, coach.

513
00:30:20,050 --> 00:30:22,005
 Way to shake it off.

514
00:30:22,005 --> 00:30:25,910
 Hey Coach, what do I do now?

515
00:30:25,910 --> 00:30:27,420
I've never actually been on base before.

516
00:30:30,260 --> 00:30:34,140
 Well, Mr. Godfrey's coaching first, you just listen to him.

517
00:30:34,140 --> 00:30:36,660
 Gotcha.

518
00:30:36,660 --> 00:30:43,590
ANNOUNCER: Now coming to bat, number one, Josh Connolly.

519
00:30:43,590 --> 00:30:45,570
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

520
00:30:51,510 --> 00:30:52,500
[BELL DINGS]

521
00:30:52,500 --> 00:30:53,490
UMPIRE: Time!

522
00:31:00,915 --> 00:31:03,740
 Hey guys, it didn't hurt at all!

523
00:31:03,740 --> 00:31:05,153
[CHILDREN LAUGHING]

524
00:31:06,095 --> 00:31:08,190
 No wonder you guys talk like idiots.

525
00:31:08,190 --> 00:31:09,856
You're always getting hit on the head.

526
00:31:09,856 --> 00:31:12,785
 Hey, I don't want to see anybody else let the ball him

527
00:31:12,785 --> 00:31:13,685
them.

528
00:31:13,685 --> 00:31:15,230
Next person does, sits out a whole game.

529
00:31:15,230 --> 00:31:16,759
We understand each other?

530
00:31:16,759 --> 00:31:17,717
Huh?

531
00:31:17,717 --> 00:31:19,633
CHILDREN: Yes, sir.

532
00:31:19,633 --> 00:31:22,990
 Man!

533
00:31:22,990 --> 00:31:24,601
Hey!

534
00:31:24,601 --> 00:31:26,850
Two on, nobody out.

535
00:31:26,850 --> 00:31:28,210
Nervous?

536
00:31:28,210 --> 00:31:29,665
Great!

537
00:31:29,665 --> 00:31:31,834
ANNOUNCER: Next up for the Panthers,

538
00:31:31,834 --> 00:31:36,316
number three, Lucky Diamond.

539
00:31:36,316 --> 00:31:37,810
UMPIRE: Play ball!

540
00:31:41,296 --> 00:31:43,288
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

541
00:31:55,240 --> 00:31:56,734
[CRACK OF BAT]

542
00:31:56,734 --> 00:31:58,726
[SENTIMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING]

543
00:32:02,710 --> 00:32:05,200
 Oh yeah!

544
00:32:05,200 --> 00:32:07,288
Yes!

545
00:32:07,288 --> 00:32:08,188
Yes!

546
00:32:11,176 --> 00:32:14,662
Man, he nailed it!

547
00:32:14,662 --> 00:32:16,654
[CROWD CHEERING]

548
00:32:36,076 --> 00:32:37,570
Good game, guys.

549
00:32:55,000 --> 00:32:57,040
 Hey Lucky.

550
00:32:57,040 --> 00:32:58,380
Your folks come to the game today?

551
00:33:05,360 --> 00:33:07,310
Listen, if you don't have to be home any time soon,

552
00:33:07,310 --> 00:33:09,860
why don't you come over and have dinner with my wife and me.

553
00:33:09,860 --> 00:33:12,544
I can take you home afterward.

554
00:33:12,544 --> 00:33:13,630
Yeah?

555
00:33:13,630 --> 00:33:14,530
Come on.

