 Get the ball, Charlie!

826
00:53:47,294 --> 00:53:48,194
Run!

827
00:53:54,668 --> 00:53:56,660
UMPIRE: He's out!

828
00:53:56,660 --> 00:53:58,154
 Third, Charlie, third!

829
00:53:58,154 --> 00:54:01,640
 Third base, throw it to third base!

830
00:54:09,110 --> 00:54:10,604
UMPIRE: You're out!

831
00:54:17,078 --> 00:54:18,074
He's out!

832
00:54:21,988 --> 00:54:22,888
ANNOUNCER: Holy cow!

833
00:54:22,888 --> 00:54:25,046
That was a triple play!

834
00:54:25,046 --> 00:54:28,532
[CHILDREN AND AUDIENCE YELLING  AND APPLAUDING]

835
00:54:28,532 --> 00:54:30,026
 Oh, man!

836
00:54:30,026 --> 00:54:32,516
 See, I told him I could pitch.

837
00:54:32,516 --> 00:54:35,504
ANNOUNCER: Congratulations!

838
00:54:35,504 --> 00:54:39,488
Boy, these kids were playing some ball.

839
00:54:39,488 --> 00:54:42,476
Drive safely and we'll see you next week.

840
00:54:44,980 --> 00:54:46,380
 Well, that's too bad.

841
00:54:46,380 --> 00:54:48,010
I was sure Lucky's father would stick around.

842
00:54:50,962 --> 00:54:51,946
Mr. Godfrey?

843
00:55:00,310 --> 00:55:02,278
Mr. Godfrey?

844
00:55:02,278 --> 00:55:04,760
 Where am I?

845
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:08,280
 You're at the ball field, remember?

846
00:55:08,280 --> 00:55:11,452
 Oh-- oh, Bill, yeah.

847
00:55:11,452 --> 00:55:12,352
Yeah.

848
00:55:12,352 --> 00:55:14,080
 Listen, are you all right?

849
00:55:14,080 --> 00:55:19,650
 Yeah, I'm-- just very tired.

850
00:55:19,650 --> 00:55:22,227
 Why don't I take you home.

851
00:55:22,227 --> 00:55:23,724
 Yeah, good.

852
00:55:36,199 --> 00:55:38,700
Did we win?

853
00:55:38,700 --> 00:55:40,461
 Yes, sir, we did.

854
00:55:40,461 --> 00:55:43,940
 I really hate to lose.

855
00:55:43,940 --> 00:55:59,850
 So do I.

856
00:55:59,850 --> 00:56:01,950
Well, Hilton, this is a surprise.

857
00:56:01,950 --> 00:56:05,370
 You know, a family used to live here before the school

858
00:56:05,370 --> 00:56:06,390
bought this place.

859
00:56:06,390 --> 00:56:08,640
Furman, I think was their name.

860
00:56:08,640 --> 00:56:11,370
This was the little girl's bedroom.

861
00:56:11,370 --> 00:56:15,350
Loud girl, always yelling about something.

862
00:56:15,350 --> 00:56:19,050
 Hilton, is there anything you don't know about?

863
00:56:19,050 --> 00:56:22,590
 I try to know just enough about everything and everybody,

864
00:56:22,590 --> 00:56:26,500
you never know when it might come in handy.

865
00:56:26,500 --> 00:56:30,360
Bill, there was an accident today up at the notch.

866
00:56:30,360 --> 00:56:32,200
 Oh, what happened?

867
00:56:32,200 --> 00:56:35,160
 It seems a couple of loggers were loading up a skidder out

868
00:56:35,160 --> 00:56:38,390
past the Goshen trail, and apparently something snapped,

869
00:56:38,390 --> 00:56:42,180
and the logs came pouring off the skidder like a tidal wave.

870
00:56:42,180 --> 00:56:44,640
One of the loggers was killed instantly.

871
00:56:44,640 --> 00:56:46,710
Jeff Grout.

872
00:56:46,710 --> 00:56:48,100
 What happened to the other guy?

873
00:56:48,100 --> 00:56:50,220
 He ran away.

874
00:56:50,220 --> 00:56:51,570
The state police believe this means

875
00:56:51,570 --> 00:56:53,145
it was something more than an accident

876
00:56:53,145 --> 00:56:57,630
but I prefer not to think that way.

877
00:56:57,630 --> 00:57:01,260
 Hilton, why are you telling me this?

878
00:57:01,260 --> 00:57:04,590
 The logger who ran away was Lucky's father.

879
00:57:04,590 --> 00:57:07,716
They have a warrant out for him.

880
00:57:07,716 --> 00:57:09,138
 Oh, no.

881
00:57:14,360 --> 00:57:15,650
Does Lucky know about it?

882
00:57:15,650 --> 00:57:18,481
 My wife went to get him, he's with the state police now .

883
00:57:23,410 --> 00:57:25,190
 I appreciate you telling me.

884
00:57:25,190 --> 00:57:27,160
 Well, I thought you should know.

885
00:57:30,700 --> 00:57:33,030
Even if his father comes back, the state

886
00:57:33,030 --> 00:57:36,872
will never let him keep custody of the boy now, not after this.

887
00:57:36,872 --> 00:57:41,310
They will probably put him in some state foster home.

888
00:57:41,310 --> 00:57:44,420
Too bad, he's a good kid.

889
00:57:50,240 --> 00:57:54,050
You know, maybe you and I can put our heads together and come

890
00:57:54,050 --> 00:57:55,190
up with something better.

891
00:57:55,190 --> 00:57:56,090
What do you say?

892
00:57:58,820 --> 00:58:01,040
You're hurting, Bill.

893
00:58:01,040 --> 00:58:02,930
Everybody can see it.

894
00:58:02,930 --> 00:58:05,540
Who knows, maybe this could help it get better.

895
00:58:08,190 --> 00:58:09,300
 Don't put me in this position.

896
00:58:09,300 --> 00:58:10,340
 Sounds like a good idea.

897
00:58:10,340 --> 00:58:11,240
 I can't do it!

898
00:58:11,240 --> 00:58:12,600
 The boy thinks the world of you.

899
00:58:12,600 --> 00:58:13,500
 No!

900
00:58:22,580 --> 00:58:27,190
 I'll stop by your place and see how he's doing.

901
00:58:27,190 --> 00:58:29,240
 That would mean a lot to him.

902
00:58:36,920 --> 00:58:41,650
Just remember, nothing in this world happened by accident.

903
00:58:41,650 --> 00:58:43,990
There's a reason for everything.

904
00:58:43,990 --> 00:58:46,854
You just have to look deep enough to find it.

905
00:59:12,542 --> 00:59:24,398
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

906
00:59:24,398 --> 00:59:26,970
 Hi, Eunice.

907
00:59:26,970 --> 00:59:29,285
I just stopped by to see how Lucky is doing.

908
00:59:29,285 --> 00:59:30,185
 Come on in.

909
00:59:30,185 --> 00:59:34,298
 He's in the den watching some baseball.

910
00:59:34,298 --> 00:59:36,150
 Where's Hilton?

911
00:59:36,150 --> 00:59:37,940
 I send him out to the store.

912
00:59:37,940 --> 00:59:40,994
Sometimes I think it's best just to get him out from under foot.

913
00:59:40,994 --> 00:59:55,754
[SOUND OF BASEBALL GAME ON TV]

914
00:59:55,754 --> 00:59:57,120
 Hey, buddy.

915
01:00:08,410 --> 01:00:09,310
I can't stay.

916
01:00:09,310 --> 01:00:11,045
I just wanted to--

917
01:00:11,045 --> 01:00:12,500
just wanted to stop by.

918
01:00:20,966 --> 01:00:23,056
Maybe I could sit with you for a minute

919
01:00:23,056 --> 01:00:24,902
and watch some of the game.

920
01:00:24,902 --> 01:00:26,055
That all right?

921
01:00:57,290 --> 01:00:58,930
 How is he?

922
01:00:58,930 --> 01:00:59,830
 He'll be OK.

923
01:01:04,340 --> 01:01:07,830
Hilton thinks the boy's father will lose custody of Lucky,

924
01:01:07,830 --> 01:01:10,330
if they ever find the guy.

925
01:01:10,330 --> 01:01:12,550
 From what we saw, he didn't appear to be much of a father

926
01:01:12,550 --> 01:01:14,304
anyway.

927
01:01:14,304 --> 01:01:15,768
 That's true.

928
01:01:19,672 --> 01:01:22,390
 You know, Hilton came up with this crazy idea

929
01:01:22,390 --> 01:01:26,810
that maybe you and I should consider taking Lucky in.

930
01:01:31,550 --> 01:01:33,640
 What did you say?

931
01:01:33,640 --> 01:01:36,250
 I said, no, of course.

932
01:01:36,250 --> 01:01:39,810
There's all kinds of reasons why we can't.

933
01:01:39,810 --> 01:01:48,540
I mean, we're still adjusting and, well, we just can't.

934
01:01:48,540 --> 01:01:53,170
 Shouldn't we at least have talked about it?

935
01:01:53,170 --> 01:01:54,950
 Why, you think I should have said yes?

936
01:01:54,950 --> 01:01:57,561
 No, no, I just thought--

937
01:01:57,561 --> 01:02:00,830
 What?

938
01:02:00,830 --> 01:02:02,550
 I just-- I just--

939
01:02:02,550 --> 01:02:03,624
 What?

940
01:02:03,624 --> 01:02:06,410
 I just-- I can't believe what kind of a day it's been,

941
01:02:06,410 --> 01:02:08,148
I just can't believe it.

942
01:02:29,630 --> 01:02:33,007
 Do not tell me they make you wash your own patrol car.

943
01:02:33,007 --> 01:02:35,300
 Nah, they give me a little cleaning

944
01:02:35,300 --> 01:02:37,850
allowance in my check each week but if I

945
01:02:37,850 --> 01:02:39,080
choose to do it myself--

946
01:02:39,080 --> 01:02:40,640
 Every little bit helps.

947
01:02:40,640 --> 01:02:42,140
 Exactly.

948
01:02:42,140 --> 01:02:44,670
Listen, Jamie, I hear there was quite an accident up on Hilton

949
01:02:44,670 --> 01:02:46,550
Burberry's property yesterday.

950
01:02:46,550 --> 01:02:47,990
 Yes, I was.

951
01:02:47,990 --> 01:02:50,340
 Mind if I ask you a couple of questions about that?

952
01:02:50,340 --> 01:02:52,220
 Sure.

953
01:02:52,220 --> 01:02:55,333
I don't know that I'll answer them, but shoot.

954
01:02:55,333 --> 01:02:57,800
 You were the first trooper there, right?

955
01:02:57,800 --> 01:03:00,516
 Yeah, I was pretty close when the call came in.

956
01:03:00,516 --> 01:03:02,540
 Pretty bad, was it?

957
01:03:02,540 --> 01:03:04,380
 I've seen worse.

958
01:03:04,380 --> 01:03:06,020
Logging is a pretty dangerous business.

959
01:03:08,880 --> 01:03:11,880
 Jamie, was he alone up there?

960
01:03:11,880 --> 01:03:13,170
 Well, of course he was.

961
01:03:13,170 --> 01:03:14,610
You know, Jeff always worked alone.

962
01:03:14,610 --> 01:03:17,160
Why?

963
01:03:17,160 --> 01:03:19,580
 You're sure there was nobody with him?

964
01:03:19,580 --> 01:03:22,200
 Like who?

965
01:03:22,200 --> 01:03:23,240
 Lucky Diamond's father.

966
01:03:27,650 --> 01:03:29,040
 Don't know him.

967
01:03:29,040 --> 01:03:30,548
 Well, he's a logger.

968
01:03:30,548 --> 01:03:33,120
 Really?

969
01:03:33,120 --> 01:03:34,020
Never heard of him.

970
01:03:48,900 --> 01:03:50,388
BILL: Let's go!

971
01:03:50,388 --> 01:03:51,380
Everybody in.

972
01:03:55,844 --> 01:03:57,828
Come on, let's move!

973
01:03:57,828 --> 01:04:01,660
Why aren't you sweating?

974
01:04:01,660 --> 01:04:04,570
All right, now it's extremely important

975
01:04:04,570 --> 01:04:09,420
to anticipate what you would do if a ball were hit to you.

976
01:04:09,420 --> 01:04:10,490
Melissa?

977
01:04:10,490 --> 01:04:11,928
You with me on this?

978
01:04:11,928 --> 01:04:13,880
 Uh-huh.

979
01:04:13,880 --> 01:04:15,160
 Uh-huh, OK.

980
01:04:15,160 --> 01:04:16,570
We'll be starting with the infield.

981
01:04:16,570 --> 01:04:19,974
Charlie, man on first and third, one out, ball

982
01:04:19,974 --> 01:04:20,940
hit to third, what do you do?

983
01:04:20,940 --> 01:04:24,310
 Hope I wasn't playing third base.

984
01:04:24,310 --> 01:04:25,960
BILL: Let's say you were.

985
01:04:25,960 --> 01:04:27,406
What would you do?

986
01:04:27,406 --> 01:04:30,370
 Well, I'd miss it.

987
01:04:30,370 --> 01:04:33,670
But the ball would probably hit me in the chest.

988
01:04:33,670 --> 01:04:36,400
 Keeping the ball in front of you, that's good.

989
01:04:36,400 --> 01:04:40,810
 And then I'd see if the guy on third was going home.

990
01:04:40,810 --> 01:04:41,710
 That's very good.

991
01:04:41,710 --> 01:04:44,280
That's excellent.

992
01:04:44,280 --> 01:04:46,510
 Hey, coach?

993
01:04:46,510 --> 01:04:48,690
 Yeah.

994
01:04:48,690 --> 01:04:50,120
 Why did Nathaniel have to die?

995
01:04:55,310 --> 01:04:58,150
 Why do you ask that now, Charlie?

996
01:04:58,150 --> 01:05:00,860
 I don't know, I just thought of it.

997
01:05:00,860 --> 01:05:01,860
MELISSA: Why did he?

998
01:05:01,860 --> 01:05:02,760
 Yeah, why?

999
01:05:08,900 --> 01:05:13,080
 Well-- I can't tell you why.

1000
01:05:16,030 --> 01:05:18,938
But he got really sick.

1001
01:05:18,938 --> 01:05:23,130
And sometimes when people get really sick, they die.

1002
01:05:25,990 --> 01:05:28,828
 Even kids?

1003
01:05:28,828 --> 01:05:31,313
 Yeah, even kids.

1004
01:05:38,271 --> 01:05:40,259
 I miss him.

1005
01:05:40,259 --> 01:05:41,750
 So do I.

1006
01:05:41,750 --> 01:05:44,732
 Me, too.

1007
01:05:44,732 --> 01:05:48,730
 I miss him, too.

1008
01:05:48,730 --> 01:05:50,480
 He was pretty funny.

1009
01:05:50,480 --> 01:05:52,740
 Yeah, he did that thing where he'd

1010
01:05:52,740 --> 01:05:53,940
turn his eyelids inside out.

1011
01:05:53,940 --> 01:05:55,096
[CHILDREN ALL LAUGH]

1012
01:05:55,096 --> 01:05:57,460
 And he could make real loud armpit noises.

1013
01:06:00,690 --> 01:06:03,900
 He was cool.

1014
01:06:03,900 --> 01:06:06,120
 Yes, he was.

1015
01:06:06,120 --> 01:06:07,020
He was very cool.

1016
01:06:16,260 --> 01:06:19,470
 OK, game Thursday, don't forget.

1017
01:06:19,470 --> 01:06:20,788
Get outta here, go on.

1018
01:06:20,788 --> 01:06:21,784
Hit the showers.

1019
01:06:38,218 --> 01:06:39,214
 Hey!

1020
01:06:39,214 --> 01:06:40,230
 Hi!

1021
01:06:40,230 --> 01:06:42,380
What are you doing here?

1022
01:06:42,380 --> 01:06:44,950
 Oh, I thought I'd like to watch you in action.

1023
01:06:44,950 --> 01:06:46,354
Where's Mr. Godfrey?

1024
01:06:46,354 --> 01:06:47,620
I don't know, he didn't show up today.

1025
01:06:47,620 --> 01:06:50,120
 Did Hilton call?

1026
01:06:50,120 --> 01:06:52,030
 No, you didn't talk to him today?

1027
01:06:52,030 --> 01:06:54,640
 No, he never returned my calls.

1028
01:06:54,640 --> 01:06:58,046
Listen, honey, I ought to find out what's going on.

1029
01:06:58,046 --> 01:07:00,580
Why did he lie about the accident?

1030
01:07:00,580 --> 01:07:02,760
 I don't know, but I don't want you to talk to Lucky about it.

1031
01:07:02,760 --> 01:07:05,555
I mean, maybe his father was unemployed, he was embarrassed.

1032
01:07:05,555 --> 01:07:08,440
He's going through a lot right now.

1033
01:07:08,440 --> 01:07:09,340
 OK.

1034
01:07:09,340 --> 01:07:10,624
 OK.

1035
01:07:10,624 --> 01:07:12,460
 Wanna go get some ice cream?

1036
01:07:12,460 --> 01:07:14,200
 Yeah, sure.

1037
01:07:14,200 --> 01:07:17,240
 Want to take Lucky?

1038
01:07:17,240 --> 01:07:19,839
I said take him for some ice cream, not adopt him.

1039
01:07:58,262 --> 01:08:05,375
[CLASSICAL MUSIC, SUBDUED  CONVERSATION]

1040
01:08:05,375 --> 01:08:06,275
 Bill!

1041
01:08:15,080 --> 01:08:16,218
 Hilton?

1042
01:08:16,218 --> 01:08:18,439
You're suddenly a very hard man to get a hold of.

1043
01:08:18,439 --> 01:08:20,630
 Been busy.

1044
01:08:20,630 --> 01:08:23,029
Why don't you stop by the house tonight and we'll talk.

1045
01:08:23,029 --> 01:08:26,470
 No, I think we'll talk now.

1046
01:08:26,470 --> 01:08:29,420
 I'm afraid this young man has a lot on his mind.

1047
01:08:29,420 --> 01:08:32,200
 No problem, I was finished anyway.

1048
01:08:32,200 --> 01:08:33,260
I'll see you later.

1049
01:08:35,924 --> 01:08:37,380
 Have you had lunch?

1050
01:08:37,380 --> 01:08:38,840
 No.

1051
01:08:38,840 --> 01:08:40,050
 Want some?

1052
01:08:40,050 --> 01:08:42,939
The shrimp and strawberry soup sounds horrible

1053
01:08:42,939 --> 01:08:45,214
but it was surprisingly good.

1054
01:08:45,214 --> 01:08:48,100
 I didn't come here to eat lunch or talk about soup,

1055
01:08:48,100 --> 01:08:50,649
Hilton, you know that. - I know.

1056
01:08:50,649 --> 01:08:53,680
You came because I'm not as sharp as I used to be.

1057
01:08:53,680 --> 01:08:55,510
 I came because you lied to me.

1058
01:08:55,510 --> 01:08:58,340
 Same thing.

1059
01:08:58,340 --> 01:09:00,979
 Why did you tell me Lucky's father was with Jeff Grout

1060
01:09:00,979 --> 01:09:02,990
when he died?

1061
01:09:02,990 --> 01:09:06,450
 Oh, now that wasn't the question I expected.

1062
01:09:06,450 --> 01:09:09,319
I was sure you were going to ask me why I didn't tell Jamie

1063
01:09:09,319 --> 01:09:11,170
Sterman or any of his patrol buddies

1064
01:09:11,170 --> 01:09:12,950
that Lucky's old man was there.

1065
01:09:12,950 --> 01:09:14,149
 He wasn't there.

1066
01:09:14,149 --> 01:09:16,930
I talked to Jamie yesterday.

1067
01:09:16,930 --> 01:09:18,859
And there was no police bulletin out for him

1068
01:09:18,859 --> 01:09:20,960
and Lucky was not waiting at the police station.

1069
01:09:20,960 --> 01:09:21,920
 That's true.

1070
01:09:21,920 --> 01:09:23,779
He was with my wife.

1071
01:09:23,779 --> 01:09:25,460
Right after I heard about the accident,

1072
01:09:25,460 --> 01:09:28,080
I went out to the trailer and picked him up.

1073
01:09:28,080 --> 01:09:29,840
 Then where was Lucky's father, because he

1074
01:09:29,840 --> 01:09:31,935
sure wasn't with Jeff Grout?

1075
01:09:31,935 --> 01:09:36,560
 Bill, you have every right to doubt me.

1076
01:09:36,560 --> 01:09:40,270
But when Jeff Grout died, Lucky's old man disappeared.

1077
01:09:40,270 --> 01:09:41,979
That's a fact.

1078
01:09:41,979 --> 01:09:45,529
 A fact, you want to explain to me why you

1079
01:09:45,529 --> 01:09:48,800
hid that fact from the police?

1080
01:09:48,800 --> 01:09:53,779
 Because I hadn't figured out yet what to do with the boy.

1081
01:09:53,779 --> 01:09:54,840
 No.

1082
01:09:54,840 --> 01:09:57,060
I don't believe you.

1083
01:09:57,060 --> 01:09:58,810
Lucky's father was never there.

1084
01:09:58,810 --> 01:10:02,790
 Bill, you're a very smart man, and you've

1085
01:10:02,790 --> 01:10:06,360
obviously done your homework.

1086
01:10:06,360 --> 01:10:08,490
But you're just going to have to trust that I know

1087
01:10:08,490 --> 01:10:09,960
what I'm doing, because I do.

1088
01:10:13,520 --> 01:10:15,660
Now, how about that soup.

1089
01:10:25,065 --> 01:10:28,530
UMPIRE: Strike one.

1090
01:10:28,530 --> 01:10:34,470
 C'mon, we need you on base, walk, single, double, anything.

1091
01:10:34,470 --> 01:10:37,450
UMPIRE: In there, strike two.

1092
01:10:37,450 --> 01:10:39,940
 C'mon Dickie, take your cuts, don't be afraid of it.

1093
01:10:39,940 --> 01:10:41,700
It can't hurt you.

1094
01:10:41,700 --> 01:10:42,700
 Are you kidding?

1095
01:10:42,700 --> 01:10:44,700
You can be killed!

1096
01:10:44,700 --> 01:10:46,700
[LUCKY TAPPING TWO BATS  TOGETHER]

1097
01:11:05,700 --> 01:11:07,200
[CHILDREN CHEERING]

1098
01:11:20,200 --> 01:11:23,200
 All right, yes.

1099
01:11:23,200 --> 01:11:25,200
All right, that's it!

1100
01:11:25,200 --> 01:11:26,200
That's a rally start!

1101
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:28,200
Let's go, Lucky!

1102
01:11:28,200 --> 01:11:29,200
 No pitcher, no pitcher!

1103
01:11:29,200 --> 01:11:30,700
Little foot, move 'em out!

1104
01:11:30,700 --> 01:11:32,200
Little bingo, baby! Good for the punch!

1105
01:11:32,200 --> 01:11:33,101
Punch it through!

1106
01:11:33,101 --> 01:11:34,666
Hit a screamer, Texas leaguer, out of the yard!

1107
01:11:34,666 --> 01:11:35,610
Take 'em deep!

1108
01:11:35,610 --> 01:11:37,312
Brown tripper, tater-tot, bat, bat, bat!

1109
01:11:37,312 --> 01:11:38,755
Gone, holy cow!

1110
01:11:45,500 --> 01:11:49,559
ANNOUNCER: Now stepping out, number three, Lucky Diamond.

1111
01:13:09,140 --> 01:13:10,847
 Good job, Lucky.

1112
01:13:10,847 --> 01:13:12,835
[CHILDREN CHEERING]

1113
01:13:45,020 --> 01:13:45,920
Hello?

1114
01:13:52,654 --> 01:13:55,060
Hello?

1115
01:13:55,060 --> 01:13:56,270
Hi.

1116
01:13:56,270 --> 01:13:59,040
Um, could you tell me where Mr. Godfrey is,

1117
01:13:59,040 --> 01:14:02,250
he didn't show up at our game today.

1118
01:14:02,250 --> 01:14:03,150
 He's dead.

1119
01:14:06,030 --> 01:14:06,930
 What?

1120
01:14:06,930 --> 01:14:08,250
 Dead.

1121
01:14:08,250 --> 01:14:09,340
Died yesterday.

1122
01:14:14,170 --> 01:14:16,585
 Oh.

1123
01:14:16,585 --> 01:14:18,050
OK.

1124
01:14:18,050 --> 01:14:19,690
Thank you.

1125
01:14:19,690 --> 01:14:20,590
Mr. Godfrey?

1126
01:14:24,255 --> 01:14:25,155
Mr. Godfrey?

1127
01:14:28,875 --> 01:14:30,710
(SHOUTING) Mr. Godfrey!

1128
01:14:30,710 --> 01:14:33,080
 What?

1129
01:14:33,080 --> 01:14:35,450
Can't you be quiet.

1130
01:14:35,450 --> 01:14:37,100
Some very old people living around here,

1131
01:14:37,100 --> 01:14:38,000
don't you know that?

1132
01:14:38,000 --> 01:14:40,070
 Well, I'm sorry, but the lady in the lobby

1133
01:14:40,070 --> 01:14:41,960
said you were dead.

1134
01:14:41,960 --> 01:14:43,430
 Oh, that's Tilda.

1135
01:14:43,430 --> 01:14:46,130
She always pulls that on visitors.

1136
01:14:46,130 --> 01:14:49,500
Sick sense of humor on that woman, but a darn good kisser.

1137
01:14:49,500 --> 01:14:50,400
Come on.

1138
01:14:50,400 --> 01:14:52,010
C'mon, I want to talk to you anyway.

1139
01:14:55,970 --> 01:14:58,610
 Wow, nice TV.

1140
01:14:58,610 --> 01:15:01,150
 Did you see the TV in the lobby?

1141
01:15:01,150 --> 01:15:03,190
Nineteen inches and no remote.

1142
01:15:03,190 --> 01:15:05,170
It's ridiculous.

1143
01:15:05,170 --> 01:15:07,830
You want to-- you want to stay for supper?

1144
01:15:07,830 --> 01:15:09,010
It's Thursday.

1145
01:15:09,010 --> 01:15:12,520
Actually, I think we have solid food tonight.

1146
01:15:12,520 --> 01:15:17,020
 No, actually, I just stopped by to make sure you were OK.

1147
01:15:17,020 --> 01:15:19,390
Maybe some other night.

1148
01:15:19,390 --> 01:15:21,690
Hopefully, another solid food night.

1149
01:15:21,690 --> 01:15:23,410
 OK, well, go on.

1150
01:15:23,410 --> 01:15:25,060
I'll see you later. - All right.

1151
01:15:25,060 --> 01:15:25,960
 Uh, no, Bill.

1152
01:15:28,940 --> 01:15:31,800
They're making me leave.

1153
01:15:31,800 --> 01:15:33,660
They're sending me to someplace in New Hampshire.

1154
01:15:33,660 --> 01:15:37,000
A place with more hands-on care.

1155
01:15:37,000 --> 01:15:39,780
I've been blanking out lately.

1156
01:15:39,780 --> 01:15:42,270
You know, like I did at the game last week.

1157
01:15:42,270 --> 01:15:45,660
 Oh well, why don't you let me talk to them?

1158
01:15:45,660 --> 01:15:47,770
 Oh no, no, please don't do that.

1159
01:15:47,770 --> 01:15:49,460
It's all right the way it is, really it is.

1160
01:15:49,460 --> 01:15:52,400
 Well, when are you leaving?

1161
01:15:52,400 --> 01:15:54,770
 Tomorrow.

1162
01:15:54,770 --> 01:15:56,980
 Tomorrow.

1163
01:15:56,980 --> 01:15:59,470
I-- we-- we've still got a couple of games left,

1164
01:15:59,470 --> 01:16:01,330
I mean the kids need you.

1165
01:16:01,330 --> 01:16:03,440
Maybe they can put this off for a while.

1166
01:16:03,440 --> 01:16:06,380
 No, no, it's OK, really.

1167
01:16:06,380 --> 01:16:08,070
I just wanted to say goodbye.

1168
01:16:08,070 --> 01:16:10,960
I just wanted to take that and don't

1169
01:16:10,960 --> 01:16:12,250
open it until you get home.

1170
01:16:15,250 --> 01:16:18,180
Bill, you've been a good friend.

1171
01:16:18,180 --> 01:16:22,110
Asking me to help with the kids has made me feel useful.

1172
01:16:22,110 --> 01:16:24,360
I haven't had many chances to feel like that lately.

1173
01:16:27,320 --> 01:16:29,196
 You should at least say goodbye to them.

1174
01:16:29,196 --> 01:16:34,610
 At my age, you kinda want to limit your goodbyes.

1175
01:16:34,610 --> 01:16:37,064
You do it for me, will you?

1176
01:16:37,064 --> 01:16:39,940
 OK.

1177
01:16:39,940 --> 01:16:45,210
 And Bill, it's good that you care for those kids.

1178
01:16:45,210 --> 01:16:46,715
But you take care of you.

1179
01:16:49,515 --> 01:16:51,990
 Me?

1180
01:16:51,990 --> 01:16:56,940
I'm fine, just fine.

1181
01:16:56,940 --> 01:16:57,930
I'm great.

1182
01:17:02,470 --> 01:17:03,370
Just great.

1183
01:17:06,340 --> 01:17:09,920
Mr. Godfrey, I'm falling apart here,

1184
01:17:09,920 --> 01:17:13,110
and I don't know what to do about it.

1185
01:17:13,110 --> 01:17:15,570
Pain is everywhere, Bill.

1186
01:17:15,570 --> 01:17:17,500
It's surrounds us all.

1187
01:17:17,500 --> 01:17:19,580
It hangs in the air waiting for us

1188
01:17:19,580 --> 01:17:22,570
and one day it decides to stick.

1189
01:17:22,570 --> 01:17:23,470
You can't avoid it.

1190
01:17:23,470 --> 01:17:26,795
You can't shake it.

1191
01:17:26,795 --> 01:17:29,652
You can only make your peace with it.

1192
01:17:29,652 --> 01:17:31,965
Now, why don't you go home to that wife of yours.

1193
01:17:37,610 --> 01:17:39,570
 I don't even know your first name.

1194
01:17:39,570 --> 01:17:41,960
 Ed.

1195
01:17:41,960 --> 01:17:42,960
 Ed.

1196
01:17:46,460 --> 01:17:49,250
Thanks for everything, Ed.

1197
01:17:49,250 --> 01:17:50,150
 My pleasure.

1198
01:17:57,320 --> 01:17:59,640
You know, one of the regrets of my life,

1199
01:17:59,640 --> 01:18:02,200
it's not something I said, something I did,

1200
01:18:02,200 --> 01:18:06,200
just that I worried too much, took things too seriously.

1201
01:18:06,200 --> 01:18:10,030
Ruby knew that and she tried to tell me, but I never got it.

1202
01:18:10,030 --> 01:18:13,350
I'd sit in the front seat and cringe and let her run

1203
01:18:13,350 --> 01:18:15,402
all the red lights.

1204
01:18:15,402 --> 01:18:17,760
Don't forget that, Bill.

1205
01:18:17,760 --> 01:18:19,810
You think of me once in a while and floor it!

1206
01:18:22,561 --> 01:18:23,460
 I will.

1207
01:18:45,645 --> 01:18:53,533
[HORN BEEPING ON COP CAR]

1208
01:18:53,533 --> 01:18:56,150
 Hey, Bill.

1209
01:18:56,150 --> 01:18:57,246
 Jamie.

1210
01:18:57,246 --> 01:18:59,940
 I was just headed out to your house to come talk to you.

1211
01:18:59,940 --> 01:19:00,860
 Something wrong?

1212
01:19:00,860 --> 01:19:03,670
 No, no, no, no, no, everything's fine.

1213
01:19:03,670 --> 01:19:05,010
I just need you to tell me everything

1214
01:19:05,010 --> 01:19:08,170
you know about Lucky's father.

1215
01:19:08,170 --> 01:19:11,730
 Oh, well, I don't know much.

1216
01:19:11,730 --> 01:19:12,660
He's a logger.

1217
01:19:12,660 --> 01:19:15,180
Drives a blue truck.

1218
01:19:15,180 --> 01:19:18,810
Doesn't seem to take much interest and his kid.

1219
01:19:18,810 --> 01:19:20,290
I've never met him.

1220
01:19:20,290 --> 01:19:22,150
 I was afraid of that.

1221
01:19:22,150 --> 01:19:24,150
I did some nosing around yesterday.

1222
01:19:24,150 --> 01:19:27,480
Put out an APB for the truck and I made some calls.

1223
01:19:27,480 --> 01:19:29,310
 Yeah, what did you find out?

1224
01:19:29,310 --> 01:19:32,070
 Well, Lucky Diamond was born in Boston.

1225
01:19:32,070 --> 01:19:34,230
And his mother was a 15-year-old runaway.

1226
01:19:34,230 --> 01:19:37,920
Other than that, we don't know anything.

1227
01:19:37,920 --> 01:19:41,020
And that truck you were talking about?

1228
01:19:41,020 --> 01:19:42,150
 Yeah.

1229
01:19:42,150 --> 01:19:43,560
 That truck belongs to Hilton.

1230
01:19:56,010 --> 01:19:57,200
 Harper?

1231
01:19:57,200 --> 01:19:58,968
 In here.

1232
01:19:58,968 --> 01:20:00,690
Oh my, I was about to send out a search party.

1233
01:20:00,690 --> 01:20:01,590
Ooh!

1234
01:20:01,590 --> 01:20:03,300
 I just saw Jamie.

1235
01:20:03,300 --> 01:20:06,120
That blue and white truck Lucky's father drives

1236
01:20:06,120 --> 01:20:07,490
belongs to Hilton.

1237
01:20:07,490 --> 01:20:09,740
 You're kidding?

1238
01:20:09,740 --> 01:20:13,910
 So he's logging Hilton's land, he's driving Hilton's truck.

1239
01:20:13,910 --> 01:20:15,280
I'm going over there to get some answers.

1240
01:20:18,080 --> 01:20:19,330
 Who's here?

1241
01:20:19,330 --> 01:20:20,400
 Lucky.

1242
01:20:20,400 --> 01:20:21,300
Eunice dropped him by.

1243
01:20:21,300 --> 01:20:22,650
He's out back.

1244
01:20:22,650 --> 01:20:25,410
You should have seen his eyes when I showed him the trains.

1245
01:20:25,410 --> 01:20:26,890
 Come on, say hello.

1246
01:20:33,507 --> 01:20:34,740
 You're out here running the trains?

1247
01:20:34,740 --> 01:20:38,250
 It took me a half hour to figure out how to turn them on.

1248
01:20:38,250 --> 01:20:39,720
We derailed them three times before we

1249
01:20:39,720 --> 01:20:40,920
finally got the hang of it.

1250
01:20:40,920 --> 01:20:41,820
Oh!

1251
01:20:41,820 --> 01:20:43,380
Lucky came up with this great idea

1252
01:20:43,380 --> 01:20:45,310
to add a mountain with a trestle.

1253
01:20:45,310 --> 01:20:47,220
Now, it'll probably cost a fortune

1254
01:20:47,220 --> 01:20:49,080
but I think we ought to try it.

1255
01:20:49,080 --> 01:20:51,870
 I thought you, um--

1256
01:20:51,870 --> 01:20:57,145
I thought you wanted to tear all that stuff out of there.

1257
01:20:57,145 --> 01:21:00,150
 Well, yeah, but that was--

1258
01:21:00,150 --> 01:21:01,620
why are you getting upset?

1259
01:21:01,620 --> 01:21:03,700
 I'm not upset.

1260
01:21:03,700 --> 01:21:06,000
Just you've never shown any interest in those trains

1261
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:07,946
before, that's all.

1262
01:21:07,946 --> 01:21:12,760
 I was always interested, you just never thought to notice.

1263
01:21:12,760 --> 01:21:14,730
Look, why don't you come join us,

1264
01:21:14,730 --> 01:21:15,990
you can talk to Hilton tomorrow.

1265
01:21:19,140 --> 01:21:21,240
 No.

1266
01:21:21,240 --> 01:21:23,250
I've got to talk to him tonight.

1267
01:21:23,250 --> 01:21:25,540
 OK, fine, fine!

1268
01:21:25,540 --> 01:21:28,900
I just thought it might be more fun for us to do this together.

1269
01:21:28,900 --> 01:21:31,920
But I guess that room always has been a little too

1270
01:21:31,920 --> 01:21:33,210
small for three people.

1271
01:21:36,030 --> 01:21:36,930
 What does that mean?

1272
01:21:39,720 --> 01:21:41,690
 There's a reason that door was always closed, Bill,

1273
01:21:41,690 --> 01:21:45,380
and it wasn't because you wanted to talk about secret guy stuff,

1274
01:21:45,380 --> 01:21:47,730
it was because you didn't want to share him with anybody,

1275
01:21:47,730 --> 01:21:49,530
not even me.

1276
01:21:49,530 --> 01:21:50,735
 That's not true.

1277
01:21:50,735 --> 01:21:54,510
 It is, Bill, you liked to keep him to yourself.

1278
01:21:54,510 --> 01:21:59,370
Baseball, trains, hiking, camping,

1279
01:21:59,370 --> 01:22:02,230
you cultivated interests with just the two of you,

1280
01:22:02,230 --> 01:22:05,600
I was always the outsider.

1281
01:22:05,600 --> 01:22:08,470
You even invented your own board games that just the two of you

1282
01:22:08,470 --> 01:22:09,750
knew how to play!

1283
01:22:09,750 --> 01:22:12,120
 We would have included you, if you'd asked.

1284
01:22:12,120 --> 01:22:13,866
 Included me!

1285
01:22:13,866 --> 01:22:15,840
Bill, we're talking about a family

1286
01:22:15,840 --> 01:22:19,490
here, not choosing sides for kickball.

1287
01:22:19,490 --> 01:22:20,390
Come on, Lucky.

1288
01:22:27,590 --> 01:22:30,260
You know why Nathaniel was an only child?

1289
01:22:30,260 --> 01:22:33,670
Why we waited so long to have another baby?

1290
01:22:33,670 --> 01:22:35,490
It's because it would have made Nathaniel

1291
01:22:35,490 --> 01:22:37,655
seem not quite so special.

1292
01:22:37,655 --> 01:22:41,010
[CRYING] And I don't think you would have

1293
01:22:41,010 --> 01:22:42,546
been able to deal with that.

1294
01:22:45,480 --> 01:22:47,800
Well, the trains are all yours, Bill.

1295
01:23:27,460 --> 01:23:28,360
 Hello, Bill.

1296
01:23:31,390 --> 01:23:34,548
I love to come out here at night.

1297
01:23:34,548 --> 01:23:38,116
I look at the lake, watch the fish jump.

1298
01:23:38,116 --> 01:23:40,270
The mosquitoes eat me alive sometimes,

1299
01:23:40,270 --> 01:23:42,760
but I guess it's worth it.

1300
01:23:42,760 --> 01:23:45,925
 Who's Lucky's father?

1301
01:23:45,925 --> 01:23:49,330
 (CHUCKLING) You're a man who likes to get right to it,

1302
01:23:49,330 --> 01:23:50,230
aren't you?

1303
01:23:52,930 --> 01:23:55,105
 Did you know his mother?

1304
01:23:55,105 --> 01:23:56,005
 Suzy?

1305
01:23:58,690 --> 01:24:01,270
No, not really.

1306
01:24:01,270 --> 01:24:04,670
She was a child.

1307
01:24:04,670 --> 01:24:09,490
She had no idea what she was getting herself into.

1308
01:24:09,490 --> 01:24:13,815
 And just what was she getting herself into?

1309
01:24:13,815 --> 01:24:16,070
HILTON: [SIGHS]

1310
01:24:16,070 --> 01:24:18,410
 Come on, Hilton.

1311
01:24:18,410 --> 01:24:20,630
Where's Lucky's father?

1312
01:24:20,630 --> 01:24:24,260
And how were you involved in all this?

1313
01:24:24,260 --> 01:24:27,710
 You know, a person can make a lot of mistakes

1314
01:24:27,710 --> 01:24:30,710
in the course of one lifetime.

1315
01:24:30,710 --> 01:24:34,020
Baseball players are no different.

1316
01:24:34,020 --> 01:24:36,080
They drink too much, they gamble,

1317
01:24:36,080 --> 01:24:38,240
they spend too much time at work, not enough time

1318
01:24:38,240 --> 01:24:40,430
with their families.

1319
01:24:40,430 --> 01:24:44,940
In short, they're just rotten Joe's just like the rest of us.

1320
01:24:44,940 --> 01:24:47,270
They just have a lot further to fall than most of us do.

1321
01:24:49,970 --> 01:24:53,300
 Lucky's father is a baseball player?

1322
01:24:53,300 --> 01:24:58,085
 Lucky's father was a baseball player.

1323
01:24:58,085 --> 01:25:03,030
Ben Slaughter, rookie of the year in 1982.

1324
01:25:03,030 --> 01:25:06,370
Sweetest swing I ever saw.

1325
01:25:06,370 --> 01:25:07,610
 He the guy--

1326
01:25:07,610 --> 01:25:10,070
 --who wrapped his car around a tree after

1327
01:25:10,070 --> 01:25:13,640
leaving a party in my house.

1328
01:25:13,640 --> 01:25:17,930
His blood alcohol was twice the legal limit.

1329
01:25:17,930 --> 01:25:21,140
They said he was doing 92 when he hit the tree.

1330
01:25:24,900 --> 01:25:28,150
Ninety-two miles an hour on a quiet suburban street.

1331
01:25:32,500 --> 01:25:36,420
Suzy Diamond came forward at the funeral

1332
01:25:36,420 --> 01:25:40,900
and told me that she was three months pregnant.

1333
01:25:40,900 --> 01:25:42,280
She was 15 years old.

1334
01:25:45,170 --> 01:25:48,380
I got her a job in Boston.

1335
01:25:48,380 --> 01:25:50,060
She never got married.

1336
01:25:50,060 --> 01:25:51,800
She worked.

1337
01:25:51,800 --> 01:25:56,890
She poured everything she had into that boy, Lucky.

1338
01:25:56,890 --> 01:25:59,780
And she died about a year ago--

1339
01:25:59,780 --> 01:26:02,150
cancer.

1340
01:26:02,150 --> 01:26:06,980
Lucky stayed with various relatives but none of them

1341
01:26:06,980 --> 01:26:10,160
had any room for him.

1342
01:26:10,160 --> 01:26:14,270
So I brought him here and I paid Jeff Grout to watch him for me

1343
01:26:14,270 --> 01:26:17,240
until I could find him a home.

1344
01:26:17,240 --> 01:26:19,190
 Meaning Harper and me.

1345
01:26:19,190 --> 01:26:21,620
 You lost a boy.

1346
01:26:21,620 --> 01:26:23,720
Everyone in town could see the pain you were in.

1347
01:26:26,320 --> 01:26:28,150
 You set us up.

1348
01:26:28,150 --> 01:26:34,200
 I told you nothing happens in this world without a reason.

1349
01:26:34,200 --> 01:26:36,660
 So getting me to coach baseball,

1350
01:26:36,660 --> 01:26:38,040
putting Lucky on my team, that was

1351
01:26:38,040 --> 01:26:40,230
all part of a big ploy to manipulate Harper

1352
01:26:40,230 --> 01:26:42,820
and me into adopting him?

1353
01:26:42,820 --> 01:26:45,640
Just who do you think you are?

1354
01:26:45,640 --> 01:26:47,880
You can't go around controlling people's lives like that!

1355
01:26:50,490 --> 01:27:00,580
 Bill, when Lucky's mother died, that boy was lost.

1356
01:27:00,580 --> 01:27:04,460
I swore to him that I would find him a home.

1357
01:27:04,460 --> 01:27:06,700
I felt I owed him that much.

1358
01:27:06,700 --> 01:27:08,100
 No!

1359
01:27:08,100 --> 01:27:11,340
You're playing God with people's lives.

1360
01:27:11,340 --> 01:27:13,220
This is not the Red Sox.

1361
01:27:13,220 --> 01:27:17,270
We're not players you can just trade around.

1362
01:27:17,270 --> 01:27:19,070
 If I had come to you four months ago

1363
01:27:19,070 --> 01:27:21,080
and asked you to take him in, would you have done it?

1364
01:27:21,080 --> 01:27:23,680
Of course not.

1365
01:27:23,680 --> 01:27:25,870
You needed time.

1366
01:27:25,870 --> 01:27:28,550
You both needed time.

1367
01:27:28,550 --> 01:27:31,200
Coaching those kids gave you that time.

1368
01:27:36,191 --> 01:27:37,090
 You had no right.

1369
01:27:39,880 --> 01:27:45,190
 Maybe not, but I did it, and I can't change it now.

1370
01:27:49,880 --> 01:27:50,780
 Redemption, Bill.

1371
01:27:55,440 --> 01:27:58,022
We all want redemption.

1372
01:27:58,022 --> 01:28:00,190
A chance to set things right.

1373
01:28:02,700 --> 01:28:04,620
To restore some semblance of order.

1374
01:28:09,570 --> 01:28:11,930
We both have a chance to do that now.

1375
01:28:14,918 --> 01:28:16,412
Don't we?

1376
01:28:16,412 --> 01:28:18,902
[GENTLE, LILTING MUSIC PLAYING]

1377
01:29:29,700 --> 01:29:33,190
 You know, Bill, God inhabits the bitter

1378
01:29:33,190 --> 01:29:35,760
and the sweet in life.

1379
01:29:35,760 --> 01:29:39,580
Ruby was always saying that and I never knew

1380
01:29:39,580 --> 01:29:40,890
what it meant until that day.

1381
01:30:19,890 --> 01:30:45,990
[QUIET, LILTING MUSIC CONTINUES]

1382
01:30:45,990 --> 01:30:47,840
 Come on.
